{
  "doc_id": "61356",
  "text": "The role of host genetic factors contributing to GAS disease has been investigated and found to play a decisive role in dictating host susceptibility to severe sepsis and STSS. Goldmann et al. utilised differential susceptibilities of distinct mouse strains to severe GAS infection to demonstrate that failure to control infection and excessive evocation of inflammatory responses by susceptible mice result in extensive tissue destruction [CITATION_1] . This finding has been refined in studies ascribing differences in severity of STSS to host polymorphism in the human leukocyte antigen complex [CITATION_2] , [CITATION_3] . Human MHC class II haplotype DRB*1501/DQB1*0602 is less commonly associated with STSS in the presence of NF, while DRB1*07/DQB1*0201 predisposes towards such disease manifestations [CITATION_4] . A complementary systems genetics approach was recently utilized to identify a panel of host genes bestowing predisposition towards severe GAS sepsis [CITATION_5] . Pathological levels of the product of one of these genes, Prostaglandin E, directly influences the severity of GAS infection [CITATION_6] .",
